FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - JAPAN (35): (MIYAZAKI) UPDATE
****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Mon 26 Jul 2010
Source: Breitbart.com, Kyodo News/Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
<http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D9H6J3LG0&show_article=1>


The Miyazaki prefectural government is set to lift its last remaining
ban on transfers of animals Monday [26 Jul 2010] midnight, leaving the
prefecture free from any restrictions on moving livestock, more than 3
months after the 1st case of foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] was
confirmed in southwestern Japan.

Miyazaki Governor Hideo Higashikokubaru plans to issue a declaration
of safety with the lifting of the ban after the epidemic severely hit
local livestock farming, forcing the prefecture to slaughter about 289
000 pigs and cows to contain the disease.

The spread of the epidemic led to temporary closures of public
facilities and cancellations of sports and other public events, while
the prefectural government asked residents in the affected and
surrounding areas to refrain from going out unless absolutely necessary.

Last week [week of 19 Jul 2010], the local government started having
vets conduct visual checks on most of the roughly 940 000 livestock in
the prefecture before it declares an official end to the epidemic in
late August [2010], when excreta disposals will be completed at the
farms affected by the epidemic.

The 1st confirmed case of FMD was reported in the town of Tsuno on 20
Apr 2010 before it spread to 11 municipalities, including Miyakonojo
city, one of Japan's biggest livestock centers.

Higashikokubaru declared a state of emergency on 18 May 2010 and
partially lifted the state of emergency rule on 1 Jul 2010 after all
animals in affected areas were culled.

The last suspected case of the epidemic was reported on 4 Jul 2010 at
a farm in the prefectural capital of Miyazaki. The area centering on
the farm is covered by the only remaining ban on animal transfers.

In related moves, the governments of Kumamoto and Oita prefectures,
which share borders with Miyazaki Prefecture, decided Monday [26 Jul
2010] to end before August [2010] the epidemic prevention measures
currently in place, including sanitization of vehicles at more than a
dozen places in each prefecture.

--
