******
[2]
Date: Sun 25 Jul 2010
Source: AsiaOne, The Yomiuri Shimbun/Asia News Network report [edited]
<http://www.asiaone.com/print/News/Latest%2BNews/Asia/Story/A1Story20100725-228760.html>


Livestock raised by more than 10 farmers in Miyazaki Prefecture had
been infected with FMD before the Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries
Ministry detected the 1st infection case on 20 Apr 2010, according to
a ministry expert team.

According to the team, led by Tomoyuki Tsuda, head of the Department
of Planning and General Administration of the National Institute of
Animal Health, the 1st infection is now confirmed to have been at a
water buffalo farm in Tsunocho in the prefecture in mid-March [2010].
The Tsunocho case initially was thought to have been the 6th of its
kind. The team believes effective initial response measures against
the disease were stymied as a result of the detection delay of the
real 1st case.

The team researched all 292 Miyazaki Prefecture farmers whose
livestock were infected to find the routes and timelines of the
infection by conducting antibody tests and other methods. An interim
report will be compiled in mid-August [2010].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Information on the buffalo farm suspected to be the index case of the
Japanese FMD epizootic, was included in ProMED-mail postings
20100605.1864, 20100722.2456, and 20100606.1890. The following RFI,
posted on 5 Jun 2010, is still valid:

"According to the OIE follow-up report number 1, submitted 23 Apr
2010, the 1st case had started already on 26 Mar 2010, in the farm
'Tsuno-cho Koyu-gun 1, Miyazaki'. The farm included 42 susceptible
buffaloes and 2 swine, among which only one case occurred (in a
buffalo). This case was diagnosed, by RT-PCR, on 23 Apr 2010, leading
to the culling of the entire farm's population (42 buffaloes and 2
swine) on 25 Apr 2010 (see outbreak 5 in
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=9167>).

"Objectively, a single, solitary sick water buffalo showing "fever and
diarrhea" is not usually expected to become subject to suspicion of
FMD. It remains to be known if this animal showed other, more typical
signs, such as oral lesions or lameness. Even if some oral lesions
were seen, such (mucosal) signs could have been mistaken for a (rare)
complication of bovine virus diarrhea (BVD), a globally distributed
pestiviral disease. Additional details on the said buffalo, including
its age, will be helpful.

"Most important, in particular for lessons to be drawn, is the
question: how and from where did the virus (which circulates in China
and South Korea) get into this Tsuno farm in the 1st place?"

For a description of FMD in water-buffaloes and an illustrated
reference, see commentary to item 1 in ProMED-mail archive no.
20100606.1890.

Hopefully, the team investigating the epizootic will manage to obtain
the afore-mentioned missing information and include it in the expected
report. - Mod.AS]
